{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review — T11 (data-migration / backfill safety):\n\nFINDING (T11, location: Acceptance Criteria — \"managed_refs survives compact_ticket\" / \"What\" §managed_refs): The plan adds a new persisted field to the SNAPSHOT `compiled_state` serialization (an overlay-triggering persisted-format change), and forward-replay reconstructs `managed_refs` for tickets with intact event history. But it is silent on ALREADY-COMPACTED legacy tickets: their pre-snapshot CREATE/LINK/parent-EDIT history is gone (folded into an existing SNAPSHOT that has NO `managed_refs` key), so on first replay `process_snapshot` restores a state with `managed_refs` absent/empty, and refs predating that snapshot can never be folded back in. Effect: for legacy tickets a current ref is NOT in `managed_refs`, so `should_propagate_removal` returns False and a deliberate local removal is silently NOT propagated — the exact churn this story exists to fix, now failing OPEN for the installed base. The plan should specify the backfill/seed behavior (e.g. seed `managed_refs` from the existing snapshot's current parent+deps on first reduce, and/or document that legacy tickets adopt-rather-than-remove until reconverged) and a back-out path.\n\n- [ ] Specify how already-compacted legacy tickets (whose pre-SNAPSHOT history is gone and whose existing SNAPSHOT lacks `managed_refs`) acquire a `managed_refs` set — e.g. seed from the current snapshot's parent+deps on first reduce — so a deliberate local removal still propagates; and state the back-out behavior on partial rollout.\n\nAFFIRMATIONS (T11): No blocking single-shot DDL / large-table lock — the change is to a derived, replay-reconstructed projection, not a separate persisted store, so no online/expand-contract DDL is required (criterion a satisfied). No giant backfill transaction — compiled_state is rematerialized per-ticket on replay/compaction, inherently incremental (criterion b satisfied). Resumability/idempotence is inherent: replay/compaction is re-runnable and deterministic, and the field's serialization is sorted for byte-parity (criterion c satisfied). The existing byte-parity guard is explicitly preserved (AC line), bounding format-change risk."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782536699232334001,"uuid":"6b9fb4d0-32af-4ccd-85f0-2bde12618bf4"}